but this is not super reader friendly. we can improve table output with kable() from the knitr package and kable_styling() from the kableExtra package.

I used the option font_size = 9 to reduce the size of the text as well

mockdata %>% 
  skim() %>% 
  knitr::kable() %>% 
  kable_styling(font_size = 9)

If youre like me and the NAs in this output are a deal breaker, try splitting the factor variables from the numeric variables so there are fewer columns to report!

The .$factor function will filter just the factor variables from the skim list.

mockdata  %>% 
  skim_to_list() %>% 
  .$factor %>% 
  knitr::kable( caption = 'Factor Variables') %>% 
  kable_styling( font_size = 9)

Tables

We also often want to create basic (or not so basic) tables of results for our reports. Create quick frequency tables with janitor

mockdata %>% 
  tabyl(ph.ecog)
 ph.ecog   n     percent valid_percent
       0  63 0.276315789   0.277533040
       1 113 0.495614035   0.497797357
       2  50 0.219298246   0.220264317
       3   1 0.004385965   0.004405286
    <NA>   1 0.004385965            NA

janitor also has a mechanism to add frequency percentages and row totals to your tables

mockdata %>% 
  tabyl(ph.ecog) %>% 
  adorn_totals("row") %>%
  adorn_pct_formatting()
 ph.ecog   n percent valid_percent
       0  63   27.6%         27.8%
       1 113   49.6%         49.8%
       2  50   21.9%         22.0%
       3   1    0.4%          0.4%
    <NA>   1    0.4%             -
   Total 228  100.0%        100.0%

and then you can add kable() and kable_styling() again to make it print how you need

mockdata %>% 
  tabyl(ph.ecog, sex) %>%
  knitr::kable(caption = 'ECOG performance score (0=good 5=dead) by Sex (Male=1 Female=2)',
               table.attr = "style='width:30%;'") %>% 
  kable_styling()
ECOG performance score (0=good 5=dead) by Sex (Male=1 Female=2)
ph.ecog 1 2
0 36 27
1 71 42
2 29 21
3 1 0
NA 1 0

Figures

Often, you want to include results in the form of figures in your reports. ggplot2 makes plotting formulaic.

Hint I removed observations with ECOG scores of 3 based on the last table.

p1 = mockdata %>% 
  filter(ph.ecog != "3") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = time, fill = ph.ecog, color = ph.ecog)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F) +
  labs(title = "Survival Time by Age of patient within \nECOG performance score groups",
       x = "Age (yrs)",
       y = "Survival Time (days)",
       fill = "ECOG Score \n(0=Good, 2=Less Good)",
       color = "ECOG Score \n(0=Good, 2=Less Good)")
p1

ggplot2 is super dynamic and includes many ways to visualize your data

p2 = mockdata %>% 
  filter(ph.ecog != "3",
         !is.na(ph.karno)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = ph.karno, y = time)) +
  geom_violin(aes(fill = ph.karno,
                  color = ph.karno),
              alpha = .2) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(color = ph.karno),
               outlier.shape = NA,
               width = .1,
               alpha = .5,
               show.legend = F) +
  labs(fill = "0 = Bad\n100 = Good",
       color = "0 = Bad\n100 = Good",
       title = "Karnofsky Performance Score \nrated by Physician",
       x = "Performance Score",
       y = "Time (days)"
       )

p2

Or, perhaps you need to include a more domain specific plot. Google for your analysis and R (or tidyverse) and see if this already exists!

Here, I demonstrate visualizing a survival analysis with the survival and survminer packages.

p3 = ggsurvplot(
    fit = survfit(Surv(time, status) ~ ph.ecog, data = lung %>% filter(ph.ecog != "3")), 
    xlab = "Days", 
    ylab = "Overall survival probability",
    legend.lab = c("0 - Good", "1 - ", "2 - Less Good"),
    legend.title = "ECOG performance score",
    risk.table = T)
p3

Sometimes, youll want to combine multiple plots of different types such as the ones weve just created. cowplot (and patchwork) lets us combine multiple plots in a grid.

First, I align the top plots and then added the survival curve to the grid!

cow1 = plot_grid(p1, p2,
          labels = c('A', 'B'), 
          label_size = 12,
          ncol = 2)

plot_grid(cow1, p3$plot, 
          label_size = 12,
          labels = c('', "C"),
          ncol = 1)
